The Secretary, in determining whether to adopt a rule or regulation under this section, shall consider:
The name of and all pertinent information that concerns the substance or additive, including, if available:
Its chemical identity and composition;
The conditions of its proposed use, including directions, recommendations, and suggestions;
Samples of the proposed labeling for the substance or additive; and
All relevant information bearing on the physical or other technical effect of the substance or additive and the quantity of the substance or additive that is required to produce the effect;
The probable composition of any substance that may be formed in or on a food, drug, or cosmetic as a result of the use of the substance or additive;
The probable amount of the substance or additive that would be consumed in the average human diet, taking into account any chemically or pharmacologically related substance in the diet;
Safety factors that, in the opinion of experts qualified by scientific training and experience to evaluate the safety of the substance or additive for its proposed use, are generally recognized as appropriate for the use of animal experimentation information;
The availability of a practicable method of analysis for determining the identity and quantity of:
The substance or the additive in or on an article;
Any other substance that is formed in or on the article because of the use of the added substance or color additive; and
The pure substance or additive and any intermediate or impurity of the substance or additive;
Any fact that supports a contention that the proposed use of the substance or additive would serve a useful purpose; and
Any other factor that is relevant to the issues of whether there is a need for the use of the substance or additive or whether the use would harm the public health.
